SIMPLE: gantlet
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gantlet
<hw>Gant"let</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<it>Gantlet</it> is
corrupted fr. <ets>gantlope</ets>; <ets>gantlope</ets> is for
<ets>gatelope</ets>, Sw. <ets>gatlopp</ets>, orig., a running down a
lane; <ets>gata</ets> street, lane + <ets>lopp</ets> course, career,
akin to l⟦oum⟧pa to run. See <er>Gate</er> a way, and
<er>Leap</er>.]</ety> <def>A military punishment formerly in use,
wherein the offender was made to run between two files of men facing one
another, who struck him as he passed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To run the gantlet</b></col>, <cd>to suffer the
punishment of the gantlet; hence, to go through the ordeal of severe
criticism or controversy, or ill-treatment at many hands.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Winthrop ran the <qex>gantlet</qex> of daily slights.</q>
<rj><qau>Palfrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Written also, but less properly,
<xex>gauntlet</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gantlet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gantlet
<hw>Gant"let</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A glove. See
<er>Gauntlet</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gantline</ent>⟦br⟧
